+/**
+ * nautilus_filesystem_is_readonly:
+ * @location: the file or directory whose containing filesystem to check
+ * @filesystem_info: (nullable): info for @location queried with at least
+ *     %G_FILE_ATTRIBUTE_FILESYSTEM_READONLY
+ *
+ * Whether the filesystem containing @location is mounted read-only.
+ *
+ * Prefer this over reading %G_FILE_ATTRIBUTE_FILESYSTEM_READONLY directly.
+ * On macOS, GLib derives that attribute from unix-mount matching, which
+ * misidentifies the enclosing mount for any path on the APFS Data volume
+ * (e.g. everything under /Users): firmlinked paths share their st_dev with
+ * the sealed read-only system volume mounted at "/", so GLib's device-based
+ * mountpoint walk selects the root mount and reports readonly=TRUE for
+ * perfectly writable locations. Distrust a TRUE answer there and verify
+ * against the kernel's own mount entry via statfs().
+ */
+gboolean
